# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: diophantine-equations
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] A **continued fraction** is a mathematical expression written as a fraction whose denominator contains a sum involving another fraction, which may itself be a simple or a continued fraction.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] If this iteration (repetitive process) terminates with a simple fraction, the result is a **finite continued fraction**; if it continues indefinitely, the result is an **infinite continued fraction**.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The special case in which all numerators $\{a_{i}\}$ (see image) are equal to one, and all denominators $\{b_{i}\}$ are positive integers, is referred to as a simple (or regular) continued fraction.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Any positive rational number can be expressed as a finite simple continued fraction, and any positive irrational number can be expressed as an infinite simple continued fraction.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Different areas of mathematics use different terminology and notation for continued fractions.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] In number theory, the unqualified term *continued fraction* usually refers to simple continued fractions, whereas the general case is referred to as **generalized continued fractions**.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] In complex analysis and numerical analysis, the general case is usually referred to by the unqualified term *continued fraction*.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The numerators and denominators of continued fractions can be sequences $\{a_{i}\},\{b_{i}\}$ of numbers or functions.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] If the sequence of convergents {*x**n*} approaches a limit, the continued fraction is convergent and has a definite value.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] If the sequence of convergents never approaches a limit, the continued fraction is divergent.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] It may diverge by oscillation (for example, the odd and even convergents may approach two different limits), or it may produce an infinite number of zero denominators *B**n*.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The story of continued fractions begins with the Euclidean algorithm, a procedure for finding the greatest common divisor of two natural numbers *m* and *n*.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] That algorithm introduced the idea of dividing to extract a new remainder – and then dividing by the new remainder repeatedly.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Nearly two thousand years passed before Bombelli (1579) devised a technique for approximating the roots of quadratic equations with continued fractions in the mid-sixteenth century.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Just 24 years later, in 1613, Pietro Cataldi introduced the first formal notation for the generalized continued fraction.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Late in the seventeenth century John Wallis introduced the term "continued fraction" into mathematical literature.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] New techniques for mathematical analysis (Newton's and Leibniz's calculus) had recently come onto the scene, and a generation of Wallis' contemporaries put the new phrase to use.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] In 1748 Euler published a theorem showing that a particular kind of continued fraction is equivalent to a certain very general infinite series.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Euler's continued fraction formula is still the basis of many modern proofs of convergence of continued fractions.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Continued fractions can also be applied to problems in number theory, and are especially useful in the study of Diophantine equations.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] In the late eighteenth century Lagrange used continued fractions to construct the general solution of Pell's equation, thus answering a question that had fascinated mathematicians for more than a thousand years.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Lagrange's discovery implies that the canonical continued fraction expansion of the square root of every non-square integer is periodic and that, if the period is of length *p* > 1, it contains a palindromic string of length *p* − 1.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] In 1813 Gauss derived from complex-valued hypergeometric functions what are now called Gauss's continued fractions.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] They can be used to express many elementary functions and some more advanced functions (such as the Bessel functions), as continued fractions that are rapidly convergent almost everywhere in the complex plane.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The long continued fraction expression displayed in the introduction is easy for an unfamiliar reader to interpret.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] However, it takes up a lot of space and can be difficult to typeset.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] So mathematicians have devised several alternative notations.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Carl Friedrich Gauss evoked the more familiar infinite product ∏ when he devised this notation: $x=b_{0}+{\underset {i=1}{\overset {\infty }{\operatorname {K} }}}{\frac {a_{i}}{b_{i}}}.$ Here, the "K" stands for *Kettenbruch*, the German word for "continued fraction".
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] This is probably the most compact and convenient way to express continued fractions; however, it is not widely used by English typesetters.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Here are some elementary results that are of fundamental importance in the further development of the analytic theory of continued fractions.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Such an object is of little interest from the point of view adopted in mathematical analysis, so it is usually assumed that all *ai* ≠ 0.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] There is no need to place this restriction on the partial denominators bi.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] to relate the numerators and denominators of successive convergents *x**n* and *x**n* − 1 to one another.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The proof for this can be easily seen by induction.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The equivalence transformation is perfectly general, but two particular cases deserve special mention.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] These two special cases of the equivalence transformation are enormously useful when the general convergence problem is analyzed.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] As mentioned in the introduction, the continued fraction $x=b_{0}+{\underset {i=1}{\overset {\infty }{\operatorname {K} }}}{\frac {a_{i}}{b_{i}}}$ converges if the sequence of convergents {*x**n*} tends to a finite limit.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] This notion of convergence is very natural, but it is sometimes too restrictive.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] It is therefore useful to introduce the notion of general convergence of a continued fraction.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Roughly speaking, this consists in replacing the $\operatorname {K} _{i=n}^{\infty }{\tfrac {a_{i}}{b_{i}}}$ part of the fraction by *w**n*, instead of by 0, to compute the convergents.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The convergents thus obtained are called *modified convergents*.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] We say that the continued fraction *converges generally* if there exists a sequence $\{w_{n}^{*}\}$ such that the sequence of modified convergents converges for all $\{w_{n}\}$ sufficiently distinct from $\{w_{n}^{*}\}$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The sequence $\{w_{n}^{*}\}$ is then called an *exceptional sequence* for the continued fraction.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] See Chapter 2 of Lorentzen & Waadeland (1992) for a rigorous definition.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The Śleszyński–Pringsheim theorem provides a sufficient condition for absolute convergence.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] It is sometimes necessary to separate a continued fraction into its even and odd parts.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] For example, if the continued fraction diverges by oscillation between two distinct limit points *p* and *q*, then the sequence {*x*0, *x*2, *x*4, ...} must converge to one of these, and {*x*1, *x*3, *x*5, ...} must converge to the other.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] In such a situation it may be convenient to express the original continued fraction as two different continued fractions, one of them converging to *p*, and the other converging to *q*.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The formulas for the even and odd parts of a continued fraction can be written most compactly if the fraction has already been transformed so that all its partial denominators are unity.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] More precisely, if the successive convergents of the continued fraction *x* are {*x*1, *x*2, *x*3, ...}, then the successive convergents of *x*even as written above are {*x*2, *x*4, *x*6, ...}, and the successive convergents of *x*odd are {*x*1, *x*3, *x*5, ...}.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] These recurrence relations are due to John Wallis (1616–1703) and Leonhard Euler (1707–1783).
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] These recurrence relations are simply a different notation for the relations obtained by Pietro Antonio Cataldi (1548-1626).
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Applying the fundamental recurrence formulas we find that the successive numerators *A**n* are {1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, ...} and the successive denominators *B**n* are {1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, ...}, the Fibonacci numbers.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Since all the partial numerators in this example are equal to one, the determinant formula assures us that the absolute value of the difference between successive convergents approaches zero quite rapidly.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] A linear fractional transformation (LFT) is a complex function of the form $w=f(z)={\frac {az+b}{cz+d}},$ where z is a complex variable, and *a*, *b*, *c*, *d* are arbitrary complex constants such that *cz* + *d* ≠ 0.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] An additional restriction that *ad* ≠ *bc* is customarily imposed, to rule out the cases in which *w* = *f*(*z*) is a constant.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The linear fractional transformation, also known as a Möbius transformation, has many fascinating properties.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Four of these are of primary importance in developing the analytic theory of continued fractions.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Here we use τ to represent each simple LFT, and we adopt the conventional circle notation for composition of functions.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Defining a finite continued fraction as the image of a point under the iterated linear fractional transformation **Τ*n***(*z*) leads to an intuitively appealing geometric interpretation of infinite continued fractions.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] In the first of these equations the ratio tends toward ⁠*An*/*Bn*⁠ as z tends toward zero.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] In the second, the ratio tends toward ⁠*An*/*Bn*⁠ as z tends to infinity.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] This leads us to our first geometric interpretation.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] If the continued fraction converges, the successive convergents ⁠*An*/*Bn*⁠ are eventually arbitrarily close together.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Since the linear fractional transformation **Τ*n***(*z*) is a continuous mapping, there must be a neighborhood of *z* = 0 that is mapped into an arbitrarily small neighborhood of **Τ*n***(0) = ⁠*An*/*Bn*⁠.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Similarly, there must be a neighborhood of the point at infinity which is mapped into an arbitrarily small neighborhood of **Τ*n***(∞) = ⁠*A**n*−1/*B**n*−1⁠.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] So if the continued fraction converges the transformation **Τ*n***(*z*) maps both very small z and very large z into an arbitrarily small neighborhood of x, the value of the continued fraction, as n gets larger and larger.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] For intermediate values of z, since the successive convergents are getting closer together we must have ${\frac {A_{n-1}}{B_{n-1}}}\approx {\frac {A_{n}}{B_{n}}}\quad \Rightarrow \quad {\frac {A_{n-1}}{A_{n}}}\approx {\frac {B_{n-1}}{B_{n}}}=k$ where k is a constant, introduced for convenience.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Intuitively, it is almost as if the convergent continued fraction maps the entire extended complex plane into a single point.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Notice that the sequence {**Τ*n***} lies within the automorphism group of the extended complex plane, since each **Τ*n*** is a linear fractional transformation for which *ab* ≠ *cd*.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] And every member of that automorphism group maps the extended complex plane into itself: not one of the **Τ*n*** can possibly map the plane into a single point.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Yet in the limit the sequence {**Τ*n***} defines an infinite continued fraction which (if it converges) represents a single point in the complex plane.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] When an infinite continued fraction converges, the corresponding sequence {**Τ*n***} of LFTs "focuses" the plane in the direction of x, the value of the continued fraction.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] At each stage of the process a larger and larger region of the plane is mapped into a neighborhood of x, and the smaller and smaller region of the plane that's left over is stretched out ever more thinly to cover everything outside that neighborhood.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The sequence {**Τ*n***} may produce an infinite number of zero denominators Bi while also producing a subsequence of finite convergents.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] These finite convergents may not repeat themselves or fall into a recognizable oscillating pattern.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Or they may converge to a finite limit, or even oscillate among multiple finite limits.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] No matter how the finite convergents behave, the continued fraction defined by the sequence {**Τ*n***} diverges by oscillation with the point at infinity in this case.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The sequence {**Τ*n***} may produce no more than a finite number of zero denominators Bi. while the subsequence of finite convergents dances wildly around the plane in a pattern that never repeats itself and never approaches any finite limit either.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Interesting examples of cases 1 and 3 can be constructed by studying the simple continued fraction $x=1+{\cfrac {z}{1+{\cfrac {z}{1+{\cfrac {z}{1+{\cfrac {z}{1+\ddots }}}}}}}}$ where z is any real number such that *z* < −⁠1/4⁠.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Euler's formula connecting continued fractions and series is the motivation for the fundamental inequalities, and also the basis of elementary approaches to the convergence problem.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Here are two continued fractions that can be built via Euler's identity.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] This last is based on an algorithm derived by Aleksei Nikolaevich Khovansky in the 1970s.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Here are three of π's best-known generalized continued fractions, the first and third of which are derived from their respective arctangent formulas above by setting *x* = *y* = 1 and multiplying by 4.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] The square root can also be expressed by a periodic continued fraction, but the above form converges more quickly with the proper *x* and *y*.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] More details on this technique can be found in *General Method for Extracting Roots using (Folded) Continued Fractions*.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Another meaning for **generalized continued fraction** is a generalization to higher dimensions.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] For example, there is a close relationship between the simple continued fraction in canonical form for the irrational real number *α*, and the way integer lattice points in two dimensions lie to either side of the line *y* = *αx*.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Generalizing this idea, one might ask about something related to lattice points in three or more dimensions.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] One reason to study this area is to quantify the mathematical coincidence idea; for example, for monomials in several real numbers, take the logarithmic form and consider how small it can be.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Another reason is to find a possible solution to Hermite's problem.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] There have been numerous attempts to construct a generalized theory.
[src:diophantine-equations/continued-fraction] Notable efforts in this direction were made by Felix Klein (the Klein polyhedron), Georges Poitou and George Szekeres.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] In mathematics, a **Diophantine equation** is a polynomial equation with integer coefficients, for which only integer solutions are of interest.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] A **linear Diophantine equation** equates the sum of two or more unknowns, with coefficients, to a constant.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] An **exponential Diophantine equation** is one in which unknowns can appear in exponents.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] The word *Diophantine* refers to the Hellenistic mathematician of the 3rd century, Diophantus of Alexandria, who made a study of such equations and was one of the first mathematicians to introduce symbolism into algebra.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] The mathematical study of Diophantine problems that Diophantus initiated is now called **Diophantine analysis**.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] While individual equations present a kind of puzzle and have been considered throughout history, the formulation of general theories of Diophantine equations, beyond the case of linear and quadratic equations, was an achievement of the twentieth century.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] However, Hilbert's tenth problem shows that there cannot exist a general algorithm that can decide whether an arbitrary Diophantine equation has an integer solution (much less to find or characterize all such solutions).
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] The simplest linear Diophantine equation takes the form $ax+by=c,$ where a, b and c are given integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] More generally, every system of linear Diophantine equations may be solved by computing the Smith normal form of its matrix, in a way that is similar to the use of the reduced row echelon form to solve a system of linear equations over a field.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Using matrix notation every system of linear Diophantine equations may be written $AX=C,$ where A is an *m* × *n* matrix of integers, X is an *n* × 1 column matrix of unknowns and C is an *m* × 1 column matrix of integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] This system is equivalent to the given one in the following sense: A column matrix of integers x is a solution of the given system if and only if *x* = *Vy* for some column matrix of integers y such that *By* = *D*.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] It follows that the system has a solution if and only if bi,i divides di for *i* ≤ *k* and *di* = 0 for *i* > *k*.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Hermite normal form may also be used for solving systems of linear Diophantine equations.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] However, Hermite normal form does not directly provide the solutions; to get the solutions from the Hermite normal form, one has to successively solve several linear equations.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Nevertheless, Richard Zippel wrote that the Smith normal form "is somewhat more than is actually needed to solve linear diophantine equations.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Instead of reducing the equation to diagonal form, we only need to make it triangular, which is called the Hermite normal form.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Integer linear programming amounts to finding some integer solutions (optimal in some sense) of linear systems that include also inequations.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Thus systems of linear Diophantine equations are basic in this context, and textbooks on integer programming usually have a treatment of systems of linear Diophantine equations.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] A homogeneous Diophantine equation is a Diophantine equation that is defined by a homogeneous polynomial.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] As a homogeneous polynomial in n indeterminates defines a hypersurface in the projective space of dimension *n* − 1, solving a homogeneous Diophantine equation is the same as finding the rational points of a projective hypersurface.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Solving a homogeneous Diophantine equation is generally a very difficult problem, even in the simplest non-trivial case of three indeterminates (in the case of two indeterminates the problem is equivalent with testing if a rational number is the dth power of another rational number).
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] A witness of the difficulty of the problem is Fermat's Last Theorem (for *d* > 2, there is no integer solution of the above equation), which needed more than three centuries of mathematicians' efforts before being solved.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] For degrees higher than three, most known results are theorems asserting that there are no solutions (for example Fermat's Last Theorem) or that the number of solutions is finite (for example Faltings' theorem).
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] For the degree three, there are general solving methods, which work on almost all equations that are encountered in practice, but no algorithm is known that works for every cubic equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Homogeneous Diophantine equations of degree two are easier to solve.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] The standard solving method proceeds in two steps.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] One has first to find one solution, or to prove that there is no solution.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] When a solution has been found, all solutions are then deduced.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] For proving that there is no solution, one may reduce the equation modulo p.
