[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] In fact, by dividing x, y, and z by their greatest common divisor, one may suppose that they are coprime.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] The squares modulo 4 are congruent to 0 and 1.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Thus the left-hand side of the equation is congruent to 0, 1, or 2, and the right-hand side is congruent to 0 or 3.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Thus the equality may be obtained only if x, y, and z are all even, and are thus not coprime.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Thus the only solution is the trivial solution (0, 0, 0).
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] This shows that there is no rational point on a circle of radius ${\sqrt {3}}$ , centered at the origin.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] More generally, the Hasse principle allows deciding whether a homogeneous Diophantine equation of degree two has an integer solution, and computing a solution if there exist.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] If a non-trivial integer solution is known, one may produce all other solutions in the following way.
