[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] The *trivial solution* is the solution where all $x_{i}$ are zero.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] If $(a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n})$ is a non-trivial integer solution of this equation, then $\left(a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}\right)$ are the homogeneous coordinates of a rational point of the hypersurface defined by Q.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Conversely, if ${\textstyle \left({\frac {p_{1}}{q}},\ldots ,{\frac {p_{n}}{q}}\right)}$ are homogeneous coordinates of a rational point of this hypersurface, where $q,p_{1},\ldots ,p_{n}$ are integers, then $\left(p_{1},\ldots ,p_{n}\right)$ is an integer solution of the Diophantine equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] It follows that solving the Diophantine equation $Q(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})=0$ is completely reduced to finding the rational points of the corresponding projective hypersurface.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] This allows parameterizing the hypersurface by the lines passing through A, and the rational points are those that are obtained from rational lines, that is, those that correspond to rational values of the parameters.
