[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] These traditional problems often lay unsolved for centuries, and mathematicians gradually came to understand their depth (in some cases), rather than treat them as puzzles.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] A father's age written in digits *AB* is the reverse of his son's age *BA*.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Also the father's age is 1 less than twice the son's age.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] A general method for such linear equations is given above, but mere inspection gives *A =* 7, *B* = 3, so that *AB* = 73 years and *BA* = 37 years.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] One may easily show this is the only solution where *A* and *B* are integer digits between 0 and 9.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Many well known puzzles in recreational mathematics lead to diophantine equations, such as the cannonball problem, Archimedes's cattle problem and the monkey and the coconuts.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] It was not until 1995 that it was proven by the British mathematician Andrew Wiles.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] In 1657, Fermat attempted to solve the Diophantine equation 61*x*2 + 1 = *y*2 (solved by Brahmagupta over 1000 years earlier).
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] The equation was eventually solved by Euler in the early 18th century, who also solved a number of other Diophantine equations.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] The smallest solution of this equation in positive integers is *x* = 226153980, *y* = 1766319049 (see Chakravala method).
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] In 1900, David Hilbert proposed the solvability of all Diophantine equations as the tenth of his fundamental problems.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] In 1970, Yuri Matiyasevich solved it negatively, building on work of Julia Robinson, Martin Davis, and Hilary Putnam to prove that a general algorithm for solving all Diophantine equations cannot exist.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Diophantine geometry, is the application of techniques from algebraic geometry which considers equations that also have a geometric meaning.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] The central idea of Diophantine geometry is that of a rational point, namely a solution to a polynomial equation or a system of polynomial equations, which is a vector in a prescribed field K, when K is *not* algebraically closed.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] The oldest general method for solving a Diophantine equation—or for proving that there is no solution— is the method of infinite descent, which was introduced by Pierre de Fermat.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Another general method is the Hasse principle that uses modular arithmetic modulo all prime numbers for finding the solutions.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Despite many improvements these methods cannot solve most Diophantine equations.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] The difficulty of solving Diophantine equations is illustrated by Hilbert's tenth problem, which was set in 1900 by David Hilbert; it was to find an algorithm to determine whether a given polynomial Diophantine equation with integer coefficients has an integer solution.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Matiyasevich's theorem implies that such an algorithm cannot exist.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] During the 20th century, a new approach has been deeply explored, consisting of using algebraic geometry.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] In fact, a Diophantine equation can be viewed as the equation of a hypersurface, and the solutions of the equation are the points of the hypersurface that have integer coordinates.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] This approach led eventually to the proof by Andrew Wiles in 1994 of Fermat's Last Theorem, stated without proof around 1637.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] This is another illustration of the difficulty of solving Diophantine equations.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] Infinite Diophantine equations are related to theta functions and infinite dimensional lattices.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] This equation always has a solution for any positive n.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] If a Diophantine equation has as an additional variable or variables occurring as exponents, it is an exponential Diophantine equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] A general theory for such equations is not available; particular cases such as Catalan's conjecture and Fermat's Last Theorem have been tackled.
[src:diophantine-equations/diophantine-equation] However, the majority are solved via ad-hoc methods such as Størmer's theorem or even trial and error.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In number theory, **Fermat's Last Theorem** (sometimes called **Fermat's conjecture**, especially in older texts) states that there are no positive integers $a,b,c,n$ with $n>2$ such that $a^{n}+b^{n}=c^{n}$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The cases $n=1$ and $n=2$ have been known since antiquity to have infinitely many solutions.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The proposition was first stated as a theorem by Pierre de Fermat around 1637 in the margin of a copy of *Arithmetica*.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Fermat added that he had a proof that was too large to fit in the margin.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Although other statements claimed by Fermat without proof were subsequently proven by others and credited as theorems of Fermat (for example, Fermat's theorem on sums of two squares), Fermat's Last Theorem resisted proof, leading to doubt that Fermat ever had a correct proof.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Consequently, the proposition became known as a conjecture rather than a theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] After 358 years of effort by mathematicians, the first successful proof was released in 1994 by Andrew Wiles and formally published in 1995.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] It was described as a "stunning advance" in the citation for Wiles's Abel Prize award in 2016.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] It also proved much of the Taniyama–Shimura conjecture, subsequently known as the modularity theorem, and opened up entire new approaches to numerous other problems and mathematically powerful modularity lifting techniques.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The unsolved problem stimulated the development of algebraic number theory in the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] For its influence within mathematics and in culture more broadly, it is among the most notable theorems in the history of mathematics.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The Pythagorean equation, $x^{2}+y^{2}=z^{2}$ , has an infinite number of positive integer solutions for x , y , and z ; these solutions are known as Pythagorean triples (with the simplest example being 3, 4, 5).
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Around 1637, Fermat wrote in the margin of a book that the more general equation $a^{n}+b^{n}=c^{n}$ had no solutions in positive integers if n is an integer greater than 2.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Although he claimed to have a general proof of his conjecture, Fermat left no details of his proof, and none has ever been found.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] His claim was discovered some 30 years later, after his death.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] This claim, which came to be known as *Fermat's Last Theorem*, stood unsolved for the next three and a half centuries and was solved with mathematics Fermat would not have known.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The claim eventually became one of the most notable unsolved problems of mathematics.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Attempts to prove it prompted substantial development in number theory, and over time Fermat's Last Theorem gained prominence as an unsolved problem in mathematics.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The special case $n=4$ , proved by Fermat himself, is sufficient to establish that if the theorem is false for some exponent n that is not a prime number, it must also be false for some smaller n , so only prime values of n need further investigation.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Over the next two centuries (1637–1839), the conjecture was proved for only the primes 3, 5, and 7, although Sophie Germain innovated and proved an approach that was relevant to an entire class of primes.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In the mid-19th century, Ernst Kummer extended this and proved the theorem for all regular primes, leaving irregular primes to be analyzed individually.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Building on Kummer's work and using sophisticated computer studies, other mathematicians were able to extend the proof to cover all prime exponents up to four million, but a proof for all exponents was considered exceedingly difficult or unachievable with the knowledge of the time.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Around 1955, Japanese mathematicians Goro Shimura and Yutaka Taniyama suspected a link might exist between elliptic curves and modular forms, two completely different areas of mathematics.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Known at the time as the Taniyama–Shimura conjecture, it had no apparent connection to Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] It was widely seen as significant and important in its own right, but was (like Fermat's theorem) considered completely inaccessible to proof.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In 1984, Gerhard Frey noticed an apparent link between these two previously unrelated and unsolved problems, and he gave an outline suggesting this could be proved.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The full proof that the two problems were closely linked was accomplished in 1986 by Ken Ribet, building on a partial proof by Jean-Pierre Serre, who proved all but one part known as the "epsilon conjecture" (see: *Ribet's Theorem* and *Frey curve*).
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] These papers by Frey, Serre and Ribet showed that if the Taniyama–Shimura conjecture could be proven for at least the semi-stable class of elliptic curves, a proof of Fermat's Last Theorem would also follow automatically.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The connection is described below: any solution that could contradict Fermat's Last Theorem could also be used to contradict the Taniyama–Shimura conjecture.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] So if the Taniyama–Shimura conjecture were found to be true, then no solution contradicting Fermat's Last Theorem could exist, meaning that Fermat's Last Theorem must also be true.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Although both problems were daunting and widely considered to be "completely inaccessible" to proof at the time, this was the first suggestion of a route by which Fermat's Last Theorem could be extended and proved for all numbers, not just some numbers.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Unlike Fermat's Last Theorem, the Taniyama–Shimura conjecture was a major active research area and viewed as more within reach of contemporary mathematics.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] However, general opinion was that this simply showed the impracticality of proving the Taniyama–Shimura conjecture.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In 1993, after six years of working secretly on the problem, Wiles succeeded in proving enough of the conjecture to prove Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Wiles's paper was massive in size and scope.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] A flaw was discovered in one part of his original paper during peer review and required a further year and collaboration with a past student, Richard Taylor, to resolve.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] As a result, the final proof in 1995 was accompanied by a smaller joint paper showing that the fixed steps were valid.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Wiles's achievement was reported widely in the popular press, and was popularized in books and television programs.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The remaining parts of the Taniyama–Shimura–Weil conjecture, now proven and known as the modularity theorem, were subsequently proved by other mathematicians, who built on Wiles's work between 1996 and 2001.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] For his proof, Wiles was honoured and received numerous awards, including the 2016 Abel Prize.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] There are several alternative ways to state Fermat's Last Theorem that are mathematically equivalent to the original statement of the problem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In order to state them, we use the following notations: let $\mathbb {N}$ be the set of natural numbers $1,2,3,\dots ,$ let $\mathbb {Z}$ be the set of integers $0,\pm 1,\pm 2,\dots ,$ and let $\mathbb {Q}$ be the set of rational numbers $a/b$ , where a and b are in $\mathbb {Z}$ with $b\neq 0$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In what follows we will call a solution to $x^{n}+y^{n}=z^{n}$ where one or more of x , y , or z is zero a *trivial solution*.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] A solution where all three are nonzero will be called a *non-trivial* solution.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] For comparison's sake we start with the original formulation.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] If n is odd and all three of *x*, *y*, *z* are negative, then we can replace *x*, *y*, *z* with −*x*, −*y*, −*z* to obtain a solution in **N**.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] If two of them are negative, it must be x and z or y and z.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] If *x*, *z* are negative and y is positive, then we can rearrange to get (−*z*)*n* + *y**n* = (−*x*)*n* resulting in a solution in **N**; the other case is dealt with analogously.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Now if just one is negative, it must be x or y.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] If x is negative, and y and z are positive, then it can be rearranged to get (−*x*)*n* + *z**n* = *y**n* again resulting in a solution in **N**; if y is negative, the result follows symmetrically.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Thus in all cases a nontrivial solution in **Z** would also mean a solution exists in **N**, the original formulation of the problem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] This is because the exponents of *x*, *y*, and z are equal (to n), so if there is a solution in **Q**, then it can be multiplied through by an appropriate common denominator to get a solution in **Z**, and hence in **N**.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] This last formulation is particularly fruitful, because it reduces the problem from a problem about surfaces in three dimensions to a problem about curves in two dimensions.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Furthermore, it allows working over the field **Q**, rather than over the ring **Z**; fields exhibit more structure than rings, which allows for deeper analysis of their elements.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The case ⁠ $n=4$ ⁠ was proved already by Fermat and could thus be ommitted.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Every positive integer greater than 2 may be written as ⁠ $pq$ ⁠ where either ⁠ $p=4$ ⁠ or ⁠ p ⁠ is an odd prime number (possibly, ⁠ $q=1$ ⁠).
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The equivalence results from the equality $x^{pq}+y^{pq}-z^{pq}=(x^{q})^{p}+(y^{q})^{p}-(z^{q})^{p}.$ So,every solution for the exponent n, if any, provides a solution for the exponent p.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Examining this elliptic curve with Ribet's theorem shows that it does not have a modular form.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] However, the proof by Andrew Wiles proves that any equation of the form *y**2* = *x*(*x* − *a**n*)(*x* + *b**n*) does have a modular form.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Any non-trivial solution to *x**p* + *y**p* = *z**p* (with p an odd prime) would therefore create a contradiction, which in turn proves that no non-trivial solutions exist.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In other words, any solution that could contradict Fermat's Last Theorem could also be used to contradict the modularity theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] So if the modularity theorem were found to be true, then it would follow that no contradiction to Fermat's Last Theorem could exist either.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] As described above, the discovery of this equivalent statement was crucial to the eventual solution of Fermat's Last Theorem, as it provided a means by which it could be "attacked" for all numbers at once.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In ancient times it was known that a triangle whose sides were in the ratio 3:4:5 would have a right angle as one of its angles.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] This was used in construction and later in early geometry.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] It was also known to be one example of a general rule that any triangle where the length of two sides, each squared and then added together (32 + 42 = 9 + 16 = 25), equals the square of the length of the third side (52 = 25), would also be a right angle triangle.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] This is now known as the Pythagorean theorem, and a triple of numbers that meets this condition is called a Pythagorean triple; both are named after the ancient Greek Pythagoras.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Thus, a Pythagorean triple is a set of three integers (*a*, *b*, *c*) that satisfy the equation *a*2 + *b*2 = *c*2.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] There are infinitely many such triples, and methods for generating such triples have been studied in many cultures, beginning with the Babylonians and later ancient Greek, Chinese, and Indian mathematicians.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Fermat's equation, *x**n* + *y**n* = *z**n* with positive integer solutions, is an example of a Diophantine equation, named for the 3rd-century Alexandrian mathematician, Diophantus, who studied them and developed methods for the solution of some kinds of Diophantine equations.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Diophantus's major work is the *Arithmetica*, of which only a portion has survived.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Fermat's conjecture of his Last Theorem was inspired while reading a new edition of the *Arithmetica*, that was translated into Latin and published in 1621 by Claude Bachet.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Diophantine equations have been studied for thousands of years.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] For example, the solutions to the quadratic Diophantine equation *x*2 + *y*2 = *z*2 are given by the Pythagorean triples, originally solved by the Babylonians (c.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Solutions to linear Diophantine equations, such as 26*x* + 65*y* = 13, may be found using the Euclidean algorithm (c.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Many Diophantine equations have a form similar to the equation of Fermat's Last Theorem from the point of view of algebra, in that they have no *cross terms* mixing two letters, without sharing its particular properties.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] For example, it is known that there are infinitely many positive integers x, y, and z such that *x**n* + *y**n* = *z**m*, where n and m are relatively prime natural numbers.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The cubic Fermat equation *x*3 + *y*3 = *z*3 was studied by Abu-Mahmud Khujandi (c.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] 940–1000), in the period of mathematics in the medieval Islamic world.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] He claimed to have proven it to have no integer or rational number solutions, but his proof is now considered faulty.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Another mathematician from later in the medieval Islamic period, Abdallah ibn Muhhammad ibn Abd al-Razzāq Ibn al-Khawwām (1243 – after 1324), a student of Nasir al-Din al-Tusi, published a list of open problems among which he included both the degree 3 and degree 4 cases of Fermat's last theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] A modern algebraic reformulation of Problem II.8 of the *Arithmetica* asks how a given squared rational number is split into two other squares of rational numbers; in other words, for a given rational number k, it asks to find rational numbers u and v such that *k*2 = *u*2 + *v*2.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Diophantus shows how to solve this sum-of-squares problem for *k* = 4, the solutions being *u* = 16/5 and *v* = 12/5.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] After Fermat's death in 1665, his son Clément-Samuel Fermat produced a new edition of the book (1670) augmented with his father's comments.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Although not actually a theorem at the time (meaning a mathematical statement for which proof exists), the marginal note became known over time as *Fermat's Last Theorem*, as it was the last of Fermat's asserted theorems to remain unproved.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] It is not known whether Fermat had actually found a valid proof for all exponents n, but it appears unlikely.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Only one related proof by him has survived, namely for the case *n* = 4, as described in the section § Proofs for specific exponents.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] While Fermat posed the cases of *n* = 4 and of *n* = 3 as challenges to his mathematical correspondents, such as Marin Mersenne, Blaise Pascal, and John Wallis, he never posed the general case.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Moreover, in the last thirty years of his life, Fermat never again wrote of his "truly marvelous proof" of the general case, and never published it.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Van der Poorten suggests that while the absence of a proof is insignificant, the lack of challenges means Fermat realised he did not have a proof; he quotes Weil as saying Fermat must have briefly deluded himself with an irretrievable idea.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The techniques Fermat might have used in such a "marvelous proof" are unknown.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Wiles and Taylor's proof relies on 20th-century techniques.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Fermat's proof would have had to be elementary by comparison, given the mathematical knowledge of his time.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Only one relevant proof by Fermat has survived, in which he uses the technique of infinite descent to show that the area of a right triangle with integer sides can never equal the square of an integer.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] His proof is equivalent to demonstrating that the equation $x^{4}-y^{4}=z^{2}$ has no primitive solutions in integers (no pairwise coprime solutions).
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In turn, this proves Fermat's Last Theorem for the case *n* = 4, since the equation *a*4 + *b*4 = *c*4 can be written as *c*4 − *b*4 = (*a*2)2.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Alternative proofs of the case *n* = 4 were developed later by many authors.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] After Fermat proved the special case *n* = 4, the general proof for all n required only that the theorem be established for all odd prime exponents.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In other words, it was necessary to prove only that the equation *a**n* + *b**n* = *c**n* has no positive integer solutions (*a*, *b*, *c*) when n is an odd prime number.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] This follows because a solution (*a*, *b*, *c*) for a given n is equivalent to a solution for all the factors of n.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] For illustration, let n be factored into d and e, *n* = *de*.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Thus, to prove that Fermat's equation has no solutions for *n* > 2, it would suffice to prove that it has no solutions for at least one prime factor of every n.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Each integer *n* > 2 is divisible by 4 or by an odd prime number (or both).
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Therefore, Fermat's Last Theorem could be proved for all n if it could be proved for *n* = 4 and for all odd primes p.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In the two centuries following its conjecture (1637–1839), Fermat's Last Theorem was proved for three odd prime exponents *p* = 3, 5, 7.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In 1770, Leonhard Euler gave a proof of *p* = 3, but his proof contained a major gap.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] However, since Euler himself had proved the lemma necessary to complete the proof in other work, he is generally credited with the first proof.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The case *p* = 5 was proved independently by Legendre and Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet around 1825.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Alternative proofs were developed by Carl Friedrich Gauss (1875, posthumous), Lebesgue (1843), Lamé (1847), Gambioli (1901), Werebrusow (1905), Rychlík (1910), van der Corput (1915), and Guy Terjanian (1987).
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The case *p* = 7 was proved by Lamé in 1839.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] His rather complicated proof was simplified in 1840 by Lebesgue, and still simpler proofs were published by Angelo Genocchi in 1864, 1874 and 1876.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Alternative proofs were developed by Théophile Pépin (1876) and Edmond Maillet (1897).
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Fermat's Last Theorem was also proved for the exponents *n* = 6, 10, 14.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Proofs for *n* = 6 were published by Kausler, Thue, Tafelmacher, Lind, Kapferer, Swift, and Breusch.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Similarly, Dirichlet and Terjanian each proved the case *n* = 14, while Kapferer and Breusch each proved the case *n* = 10.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Strictly speaking, these proofs are unnecessary, since these cases follow from the proofs for *n* = 3, 5, 7 respectively.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Nevertheless, the reasoning of these even-exponent proofs differs from their odd-exponent counterparts.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Dirichlet's proof for *n* = 14 was published in 1832, before Lamé's 1839 proof for *n* = 7.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] All proofs for specific exponents used Fermat's technique of infinite descent, either in its original form, or in the form of descent on elliptic curves or abelian varieties.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The details and auxiliary arguments, however, were often *ad hoc* and tied to the individual exponent under consideration.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Since they became ever more complicated as p increased, it seemed unlikely that the general case of Fermat's Last Theorem could be proved by building upon the proofs for individual exponents.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Although some general results on Fermat's Last Theorem were published in the early 19th century by Niels Henrik Abel and Peter Barlow, the first significant work on the general theorem was done by Sophie Germain.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In the early 19th century, Sophie Germain developed several novel approaches to prove Fermat's Last Theorem for all exponents.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] First, she defined a set of auxiliary primes θ constructed from the prime exponent p by the equation *θ* = 2*hp* + 1, where h is any integer not divisible by three.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] She showed that, if no integers raised to the pth power were adjacent modulo θ (the *non-consecutivity condition*), then θ must divide the product xyz.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Although she developed many techniques for establishing the non-consecutivity condition, she did not succeed in her strategic goal.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] She also worked to set lower limits on the size of solutions to Fermat's equation for a given exponent p, a modified version of which was published by Adrien-Marie Legendre.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Germain tried unsuccessfully to prove the first case of Fermat's Last Theorem for all even exponents, specifically for *n* = 2*p*, which was proved by Guy Terjanian in 1977.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In 1985, Leonard Adleman, Roger Heath-Brown and Étienne Fouvry proved that the first case of Fermat's Last Theorem holds for infinitely many odd primes p.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In 1847, Gabriel Lamé outlined a proof of Fermat's Last Theorem based on factoring the equation *x**p* + *y**p* = *z**p* in complex numbers, specifically the cyclotomic field based on the roots of the number 1.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] His proof failed, however, because it assumed incorrectly that such complex numbers can be factored uniquely into primes, similar to integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] This gap was pointed out immediately by Joseph Liouville, who later read a paper that demonstrated this failure of unique factorisation, written by Ernst Kummer.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Kummer set himself the task of determining whether the cyclotomic field could be generalized to include new prime numbers such that unique factorisation was restored.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] He succeeded in that task by developing the ideal numbers.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Harold Edwards said the belief that Kummer was mainly interested in Fermat's Last Theorem "is surely mistaken".
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Using the general approach outlined by Lamé, Kummer proved both cases of Fermat's Last Theorem for all regular prime numbers.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] However, he could not prove the theorem for the exceptional primes (irregular primes) that conjecturally occur approximately 39% of the time; the only irregular primes below 270 are 37, 59, 67, 101, 103, 131, 149, 157, 233, 257 and 263.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In the 1920s, Louis Mordell posed a conjecture that implied that Fermat's equation has at most a finite number of nontrivial primitive integer solutions, if the exponent n is greater than two.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] This conjecture was proved in 1983 by Gerd Faltings, and is now known as Faltings' theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In the latter half of the 20th century, computational methods were used to extend Kummer's approach to the irregular primes.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In 1954, Harry Vandiver used a SWAC computer to prove Fermat's Last Theorem for all primes up to 2521.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] By 1978, Samuel Wagstaff had extended this to all primes less than 125,000.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] By 1993, Fermat's Last Theorem had been proved for all primes less than four million.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] However, despite these efforts and their results, no proof existed of Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Proofs of individual exponents by their nature could never prove the *general* case: even if all exponents were verified up to an extremely large number X, a higher exponent beyond X might still exist for which the claim was not true.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] By accomplishing a partial proof of this conjecture in 1994, Andrew Wiles ultimately succeeded in proving Fermat's Last Theorem, as well as leading the way to a full proof by others of what is now known as the modularity theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Around 1955, Japanese mathematicians Goro Shimura and Yutaka Taniyama observed a possible link between two apparently completely distinct branches of mathematics, elliptic curves and modular forms.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The resulting modularity theorem (at the time known as the Taniyama–Shimura conjecture) states that every elliptic curve is modular, meaning that it can be associated with a unique modular form.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The link was initially dismissed as unlikely or highly speculative, but was taken more seriously when number theorist André Weil found evidence supporting it, though not proving it; as a result the conjecture was often known as the Taniyama–Shimura–Weil conjecture.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Even after gaining serious attention, the conjecture was seen by contemporary mathematicians as extraordinarily difficult or perhaps inaccessible to proof.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In 1984, Gerhard Frey noted a link between Fermat's equation and the modularity theorem, then still a conjecture.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] If Fermat's equation had any solution (*a*, *b*, *c*) for exponent *p* > 2, then it could be shown that the semi-stable elliptic curve (now known as a Frey-Hellegouarch) $y^{2}=x(x-a^{p})(x+b^{p})$ would have such unusual properties that it was unlikely to be modular.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] This would conflict with the modularity theorem, which asserted that all elliptic curves are modular.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] As such, Frey observed that a proof of the Taniyama–Shimura–Weil conjecture might also simultaneously prove Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] By contraposition, a *disproof* or refutation of Fermat's Last Theorem would disprove the Taniyama–Shimura–Weil conjecture.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In plain English, Frey had shown that, if this intuition about his equation was correct, then any set of four numbers (*a*, *b*, *c*, *n*) capable of disproving Fermat's Last Theorem, could also be used to disprove the Taniyama–Shimura–Weil conjecture.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Therefore, if the latter were true, the former could not be disproven, and would also have to be true.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Following this strategy, a proof of Fermat's Last Theorem required two steps.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] First, it was necessary to prove the modularity theorem, or at least to prove it for the types of elliptical curves that included Frey's equation (known as semistable elliptic curves).
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] This was widely believed inaccessible to proof by contemporary mathematicians.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Second, it was necessary to show that Frey's intuition was correct: that if an elliptic curve were constructed in this way, using a set of numbers that were a solution of Fermat's equation, the resulting elliptic curve could not be modular.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Frey showed that this was *plausible* but did not go as far as giving a full proof.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The missing piece (the so-called "epsilon conjecture", now known as Ribet's theorem) was identified by Jean-Pierre Serre who also gave an almost-complete proof and the link suggested by Frey was finally proved in 1986 by Ken Ribet.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] This meant that a proof of the modularity theorem would automatically prove Fermat's Last Theorem as well.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Ribet's proof of the epsilon conjecture in 1986 accomplished the first of the two goals proposed by Frey.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Wiles worked on that task for six years in near-total secrecy, covering up his efforts by releasing prior work in small segments as separate papers and confiding only in his wife.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] However, by mid-1991, Iwasawa theory also seemed to not be reaching the central issues in the problem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In response, he approached colleagues to seek out any hints of cutting-edge research and new techniques, and discovered an Euler system recently developed by Victor Kolyvagin and Matthias Flach that seemed "tailor made" for the inductive part of his proof.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Wiles studied and extended this approach, which worked.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Since his work relied extensively on this approach, which was new to mathematics and to Wiles, in January 1993 he asked his Princeton colleague, Nick Katz, to help him check his reasoning for subtle errors.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Their conclusion at the time was that the techniques Wiles used seemed to work correctly.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] By mid-May 1993, Wiles was ready to tell his wife he thought he had solved the proof of Fermat's Last Theorem, and by June he felt sufficiently confident to present his results in three lectures delivered on 21–23 June 1993 at the Isaac Newton Institute for Mathematical Sciences.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Specifically, Wiles presented his proof of the Taniyama–Shimura conjecture for semistable elliptic curves; together with Ribet's proof of the epsilon conjecture, this implied Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] However, it became apparent during peer review that a critical point in the proof was incorrect.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] It contained an error in a bound on the order of a particular group.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The error was caught by several mathematicians refereeing Wiles's manuscript including Katz (in his role as reviewer), who alerted Wiles on 23 August 1993.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The error would not have rendered his work worthless: each part of Wiles's work was highly significant and innovative by itself, as were the many developments and techniques he had created in the course of his work, and only one part was affected.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] However, without this part proved, there was no actual proof of Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Wiles spent almost a year trying to repair his proof, initially by himself and then in collaboration with his former student Richard Taylor, without success.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] By the end of 1993, rumours had spread that under scrutiny, Wiles's proof had failed, but how seriously was not known.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Mathematicians were beginning to pressure Wiles to disclose his work whether it was complete or not, so that the wider community could explore and use whatever he had managed to accomplish.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] But instead of being fixed, the problem, which had originally seemed minor, now seemed very significant, far more serious, and less easy to resolve.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Wiles states that on the morning of 19 September 1994, he had almost resigned himself to accepting that he had failed, and to publishing details of the various failed approaches he had tried, for use by others who might be able to find a way through those difficulties.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Fixing one approach with tools from the other approach would resolve the issue for all the cases that were not already proven by his refereed paper.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] He described later that Iwasawa theory and the Kolyvagin–Flach approach were each inadequate on their own, but together they could be made powerful enough to overcome this final hurdle.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] — Andrew Wiles, as quoted by Simon Singh.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The two papers were vetted and published as the entirety of the May 1995 issue of the *Annals of Mathematics*.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The proof's method of identification of a deformation ring with a Hecke algebra (now referred to as an *R=T theorem*) to prove modularity lifting theorems has been an influential development in algebraic number theory.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] These papers established the modularity theorem for semistable elliptic curves, the last step in proving Fermat's Last Theorem, 358 years after it was conjectured.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The full Taniyama–Shimura–Weil conjecture was finally proved by Diamond (1996), Conrad et al.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] (2001) who, building on Wiles's work, incrementally chipped away at the remaining cases until the full result was proved.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The now fully proved conjecture became known as the modularity theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Several other theorems in number theory similar to Fermat's Last Theorem also follow from the same reasoning, using the modularity theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] For example: no cube can be written as a sum of two coprime nth powers, *n* ≥ 3.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Fermat's Last Theorem considers solutions to the Fermat equation: $a^{n}+b^{n}=c^{n}$ with positive integers a, b, and c and an integer n greater than 2.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] There are several generalizations of the Fermat equation to more general equations that allow the exponent n to be a negative integer or rational, or to consider three different exponents.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The Beal conjecture states that there are no solutions to the generalized Fermat equation in positive integers a, b, c, m, n, k with a, b, and c being pairwise coprime and all of m, n, k being greater than 2.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The Fermat–Catalan conjecture generalizes Fermat's last theorem with the ideas of the Catalan conjecture.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] When we allow the exponent n to be the reciprocal of an integer; that is, *n* = 1/*m* for some integer m, we have the inverse Fermat equation $a^{\frac {1}{m}}+b^{\frac {1}{m}}=c^{\frac {1}{m}}.$ All solutions of this equation were computed by Hendrik Lenstra in 1992.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In the case in which the mth roots are required to be real and positive, all solutions are given by ${\begin{aligned}a&=rs^{m}\\b&=rt^{m}\\c&=r(s+t)^{m}\end{aligned}}$ for positive integers r, s, t with s and t coprime.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The case *n* = −2 also has an infinitude of solutions, and these have a geometric interpretation in terms of right triangles with integer sides and an integer altitude to the hypotenuse.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] for coprime integers u, v with *v* > *u*.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The geometric interpretation is that a and b are the integer legs of a right triangle and d is the integer altitude to the hypotenuse.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Then the hypotenuse itself is the integer $c=(v^{2}+u^{2})^{2},$ so (*a*, *b*, *c*) is a Pythagorean triple.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] There are no solutions in integers for *a**n* + *b**n* = *c**n* for integers *n* < −2.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] If there were, the equation could be multiplied through by *a*|*n*|*b*|*n*|*c*|*n*| to obtain $(bc)^{|n|}+(ac)^{|n|}=(ab)^{|n|},$ which is impossible by Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The abc conjecture roughly states that if three positive integers a, b and c (hence the name) are coprime and satisfy *a* + *b* = *c*, then the radical d of abc is usually not much smaller than c.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In particular, the abc conjecture in its most standard formulation implies Fermat's last theorem for n that are sufficiently large.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The modified Szpiro conjecture is equivalent to the abc conjecture and therefore has the same implication.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] An effective version of the abc conjecture, or an effective version of the modified Szpiro conjecture, implies Fermat's Last Theorem outright.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In 1816, and again in 1850, the French Academy of Sciences offered a prize for a general proof of Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In 1857, the academy awarded 3,000 francs and a gold medal to Kummer for his research on ideal numbers, although he had not submitted an entry for the prize.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Another prize was offered in 1883 by the Academy of Brussels.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In 1908, the German industrialist and amateur mathematician Paul Wolfskehl bequeathed 100,000 gold marks—a large sum at the time—to the Göttingen Academy of Sciences to offer as a prize for a complete proof of Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] On 27 June 1908, the academy published nine rules for awarding the prize.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Among other things, these rules required that the proof be published in a peer-reviewed journal; the prize would not be awarded until two years after the publication; and that no prize would be given after 13 September 2007, roughly a century after the competition was begun.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Wiles collected the Wolfskehl prize money, then worth $50,000, on 27 June 1997.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In March 2016, Wiles was awarded the Norwegian government's Abel Prize worth €600,000 for "his stunning proof of Fermat's Last Theorem by way of the modularity conjecture for semistable elliptic curves, opening a new era in number theory".
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Prior to Wiles's proof, thousands of incorrect proofs were submitted to the Wolfskehl committee, amounting to roughly 10 feet (3.0 meters) of correspondence.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In the first year alone (1907–1908), 621 attempted proofs were submitted, although by the 1970s, the rate of submission had decreased to roughly 3–4 attempted proofs per month.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] According to some claims, Edmund Landau tended to use a special preprinted form for such proofs, where the location of the first mistake was left blank to be filled by one of his graduate students.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Schlichting, a Wolfskehl reviewer, most of the proofs were based on elementary methods taught in schools, and often submitted by "people with a technical education but a failed career".
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] Arthur Porges' 1954 short story "The Devil and Simon Flagg" features a mathematician who bargains with the Devil that the latter cannot produce a proof of Fermat's Last Theorem within twenty-four hours.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In the 1989 *Star Trek: The Next Generation* episode "The Royale", Captain Picard states that the theorem is still unproven in the 24th century.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The proof was released five years after the episode originally aired.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] In a 1998 episode of *The Simpsons*, "The Wizard of Evergreen Terrace", Homer Simpson writes the equation 398712 + 436512 = 447212 on a blackboard, which appears to be a counterexample to Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The equation is wrong, but it appears to be correct if entered in a calculator with 10 significant figures.
[src:diophantine-equations/fermat-s-last-theorem] The 1997 book *Fermat's Last Theorem* by author Simon Singh became the first mathematics book to become a number-one seller in the United Kingdom, while Singh's documentary *The Proof*, on which the book was based, won a BAFTA award in 1997.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] By contrast, the Diophantine equation $x^{2}+y^{2}+1=0$ has no such solution.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The solution to Hilbert's tenth problem shows that such a general algorithm cannot exist.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] This is the result of combined work of Martin Davis, Yuri Matiyasevich, Hilary Putnam, and Julia Robinson spanning 21 years, with Matiyasevich completing the theorem in 1970.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The theorem is now known as Matiyasevich's theorem or the MRDP theorem (an initialism for the surnames of the four principal contributors to its solution).
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The words "process" and "finite number of operations" have been taken to mean that Hilbert was asking for an algorithm.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The term "rational integral" simply refers to the integers, positive, negative, or zero: 0, ±1, ±2, ... .
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] So Hilbert was asking for a general algorithm to decide whether a given polynomial Diophantine equation with integer coefficients has a solution in integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Hilbert's problem is not concerned with finding the solutions.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] It only asks whether, in general, we can decide whether one or more solutions exist.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The answer to this question is negative, in the sense that no "process can be devised" for answering that question.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] In modern terms, Hilbert's tenth problem is an undecidable problem.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] In a Diophantine equation, there are two kinds of variables: the parameters and the unknowns.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The Diophantine set consists of the parameter assignments for which the Diophantine equation is solvable.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] where the equation is solvable if and only if the greatest common divisor $\gcd(a_{1},a_{2})$ evenly divides $a_{3}$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The set of all ordered triples $(a_{1},a_{2},a_{3})$ satisfying this restriction is called the *Diophantine set* defined by $a_{1}x+a_{2}y=a_{3}$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] In these terms, Hilbert's tenth problem asks whether there is an algorithm to determine if the Diophantine set corresponding to an arbitrary polynomial is non-empty.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The problem is generally understood in terms of the natural numbers (that is, the non-negative integers) rather than arbitrary integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] However, the two problems are equivalent: any general algorithm that can decide whether a given Diophantine equation has an integer solution could be modified into an algorithm that decides whether a given Diophantine equation has a natural-number solution, and vice versa.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] By Lagrange's four-square theorem, every natural number is the sum of the squares of four integers, so we could rewrite every natural-valued parameter in terms of the sum of the squares of four new integer-valued parameters.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Similarly, since every integer is the difference of two natural numbers, we could rewrite every integer parameter as the difference of two natural parameters.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Furthermore, we can always rewrite a system of simultaneous equations $p_{1}=0,\ldots ,p_{k}=0$ (where each $p_{i}$ is a polynomial) as a single equation $p_{1}^{\,2}+\cdots +p_{k}^{\,2}=0$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] A recursively enumerable set can be characterized as one for which there exists an algorithm that will eventually halt when a member of the set is provided as input, but may continue indefinitely when the input is a non-member.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] It was the development of computability theory (also known as recursion theory) that provided a precise explication of the intuitive notion of algorithmic computability, thus making the notion of recursive enumerability perfectly rigorous.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] It is evident that Diophantine sets are recursively enumerable (also known as semi-decidable).
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] This is because one can arrange all possible tuples of values of the unknowns in a sequence and then, for a given value of the parameter(s), test these tuples, one after another, to see whether they are solutions of the corresponding equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] This result is variously known as Matiyasevich's theorem (because he provided the crucial step that completed the proof) and the MRDP theorem (for Yuri Matiyasevich, Julia Robinson, Martin Davis, and Hilary Putnam).
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Because *there exists a recursively enumerable set that is not computable,* the unsolvability of Hilbert's tenth problem is an immediate consequence.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] has solutions in natural numbers is not computable.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] So, not only is there no general algorithm for testing Diophantine equations for solvability, but there is none even for this family of single-parameter equations.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The Matiyasevich/MRDP theorem relates two notions—one from computability theory, the other from number theory—and has some surprising consequences.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] This is true simply because Diophantine sets, being equal to recursively enumerable sets, are also equal to Turing machines.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] It is a well known property of Turing machines that there exist universal Turing machines, capable of executing any algorithm.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] So, for example, there is a polynomial for which the positive part of its range is exactly the prime numbers.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] (On the other hand, no polynomial can only take on prime values.) The same holds for other recursively enumerable sets of natural numbers: the factorial, the binomial coefficients, the fibonacci numbers, etc.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Other applications concern what logicians refer to as $\Pi _{1}^{0}$ propositions, sometimes also called propositions of *Goldbach type*.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] These are like Goldbach's conjecture, in stating that all natural numbers possess a certain property that is algorithmically checkable for each particular number.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The Matiyasevich/MRDP theorem implies that each such proposition is equivalent to a statement that asserts that some particular Diophantine equation has no solutions in natural numbers.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] A number of important and celebrated problems are of this form: in particular, Fermat's Last Theorem, the Riemann hypothesis, and the four color theorem.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] In addition the assertion that particular formal systems such as Peano arithmetic or ZFC are consistent can be expressed as $\Pi _{1}^{0}$ sentences.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The idea is to follow Kurt Gödel in coding proofs by natural numbers in such a way that the property of being the number representing a proof is algorithmically checkable.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] $\Pi _{1}^{0}$ sentences have the special property that if they are false, that fact will be provable in any of the usual formal systems.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] This is because the falsity amounts to the existence of a counter-example that can be verified by simple arithmetic.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] So if a $\Pi _{1}^{0}$ sentence is such that neither it nor its negation is provable in one of these systems, that sentence must be true.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Then the theorem tells us that either a false statement of this form is proved or a true one remains unproved in the system in question.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] We may speak of the *degree* of a Diophantine set as being the least degree of a polynomial in an equation defining that set.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Similarly, we can call the *dimension* of such a set the fewest unknowns in a defining equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Because of the existence of a universal Diophantine equation, it is clear that there are absolute upper bounds to both of these quantities, and there has been much interest in determining these bounds.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Already in the 1920s Thoralf Skolem showed that any Diophantine equation is equivalent to one of degree 4 or less.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] His trick was to introduce new unknowns by equations setting them equal to the square of an unknown or the product of two unknowns.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Repetition of this process results in a system of second degree equations; then an equation of degree 4 is obtained by summing the squares.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] So every Diophantine set is trivially of degree 4 or less.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] It is not known whether this result is best possible.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Julia Robinson and Yuri Matiyasevich showed that every Diophantine set has dimension no greater than 13.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Later, Matiyasevich sharpened their methods to show that 9 unknowns suffice.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Although it may well be that this result is not the best possible, there has been no further progress.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] So, in particular, there is no algorithm for testing Diophantine equations with 9 or fewer unknowns for solvability in natural numbers.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] For the case of rational integer solutions (as Hilbert had originally posed it), the 4-squares trick shows that there is no algorithm for equations with no more than 36 unknowns.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] But Zi-Wei Sun showed that the problem for integers is unsolvable even for equations with no more than 11 unknowns.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Martin Davis studied algorithmic questions involving the number of solutions of a Diophantine equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Hilbert's tenth problem asks whether or not that number is 0.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Davis proved that there is no algorithm to test a given Diophantine equation to determine whether the number of its solutions is a member of the set C .
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Thus there is no algorithm to determine whether the number of solutions of a Diophantine equation is finite, odd, a perfect square, a prime, etc.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The proof of the MRDP theorem has been formalized in Rocq (previously known as *Coq*).
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Although Hilbert posed the problem for the rational integers, it can be just as well asked for many rings (in particular, for any ring whose number of elements is countable).
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Obvious examples are the rings of integers of algebraic number fields as well as the rational numbers.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] There has been much work on Hilbert's tenth problem for the rings of integers of algebraic number fields.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Basing themselves on earlier work by Jan Denef and Leonard Lipschitz and using class field theory, Harold N.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Shlapentokh and Thanases Pheidas (independently of one another) obtained the same result for algebraic number fields admitting exactly one pair of complex conjugate embeddings.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] The problem for the ring of integers of algebraic number fields other than those covered by the results above remains open.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Likewise, despite much interest, the problem for equations over the rationals remains open.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Barry Mazur has conjectured that for any variety over the rationals, the topological closure over the reals of the set of solutions has only finitely many components.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] This conjecture implies that the integers are not Diophantine over the rationals, and so if this conjecture is true, a negative answer to Hilbert's Tenth Problem would require a different approach than that used for other rings.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] In 2024, Peter Koymans and Carlo Pagano published a claimed proof that Hilbert's 10th problem is undecidable for every ring of integers using additive combinatorics.
[src:diophantine-equations/hilbert-s-tenth-problem] Another team of mathematicians subsequently claimed another proof of the same result, using different methods.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] This kind of equation was first studied extensively in India starting with Brahmagupta, who found an integer solution to $92x^{2}+1=y^{2}$ in his *Brāhmasphuṭasiddhānta* circa 628.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Bhaskara II in the 12th century and Narayana Pandit in the 14th century both found general solutions to Pell's equation and other quadratic indeterminate equations.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Bhaskara II is generally credited with developing the *chakravala* method, building on the work of Jayadeva and Brahmagupta.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Solutions to specific examples of Pell's equation, such as the Pell numbers arising from the equation with *n* = 2, had been known for much longer, since the time of Pythagoras in Greece and a similar date in India.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] William Brouncker was the first European to solve Pell's equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The name of Pell's equation arose from Leonhard Euler mistakenly attributing Brouncker's solution of the equation to John Pell.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] As early as 400 BC in India and Greece, mathematicians studied the numbers arising from the *n* = 2 case of Pell's equation, $x^{2}-2y^{2}=1,$ and from the closely related equation $x^{2}-2y^{2}=-1$ because of the connection of these equations to the square root of 2.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Indeed, if *x* and *y* are positive integers satisfying this equation, then *x*/*y* is an approximation of √2.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The numbers *x* and *y* appearing in these approximations, called side and diameter numbers, were known to the Pythagoreans, and Proclus observed that in the opposite direction these numbers obeyed one of these two equations.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Similarly, Baudhayana discovered that *x* = 17, *y* = 12 and *x* = 577, *y* = 408 are two solutions to the Pell equation, and that 17/12 and 577/408 are very close approximations to the square root of 2.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Later, Archimedes approximated the square root of 3 by the rational number 1351/780.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Although he did not explain his methods, this approximation may be obtained in the same way, as a solution to Pell's equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Likewise, Archimedes's cattle problem—an ancient word problem about finding the number of cattle belonging to the sun god Helios—can be solved by reformulating it as a Pell's equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The manuscript containing the problem states that it was devised by Archimedes and recorded in a letter to Eratosthenes, and the attribution to Archimedes is generally accepted today.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Around AD 250, Diophantus considered the equation $a^{2}x^{2}+c=y^{2},$ where *a* and *c* are fixed numbers, and *x* and *y* are the variables to be solved for.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] This equation is different in form from Pell's equation but equivalent to it.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Al-Karaji, a 10th-century Persian mathematician, worked on similar problems to Diophantus.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Not only did this give a way to generate infinitely many solutions to $x^{2}-Ny^{2}=1$ starting with one solution, but also, by dividing such a composition by $k_{1}k_{2}$ , integer or "nearly integer" solutions could often be obtained.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Dividing throughout by 64 ("8" for x and y ) gave the triple (24, 5/2, 1), which when composed with itself gave the desired integer solution (1151, 120, 1).
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Brahmagupta solved many Pell's equations with this method, proving that it gives solutions starting from an integer solution of $x^{2}-Ny^{2}=k$ for *k* = ±1, ±2, or ±4.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The first general method for solving the Pell's equation (for all *N*) was given by Bhāskara II in 1150, extending the methods of Brahmagupta.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] When m is chosen so that ${\frac {a+bm}{k}}$ is an integer, so are the other two numbers in the triple.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Among such m , the method chooses one that minimizes ${\frac {m^{2}-N}{k}}$ and repeats the process.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] This method always terminates with a solution.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Several European mathematicians rediscovered how to solve Pell's equation in the 17th century.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Pierre de Fermat found how to solve the equation and in a 1657 letter issued it as a challenge to English mathematicians.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] In a letter to Kenelm Digby, Bernard Frénicle de Bessy said that Fermat found the smallest solution for *N* up to 150 and challenged John Wallis to solve the cases *N* = 151 or 313.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Both Wallis and William Brouncker gave solutions to these problems, though Wallis suggests in a letter that the solution was due to Brouncker.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] John Pell's connection with the equation is that he revised Thomas Branker's translation of Johann Rahn's 1659 book *Teutsche Algebra* into English, with a discussion of Brouncker's solution of the equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Leonhard Euler mistakenly thought that this solution was due to Pell, as a result of which he named the equation after Pell.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The general theory of Pell's equation, based on continued fractions and algebraic manipulations with numbers of the form $P+Q{\sqrt {a}},$ was developed by Lagrange in 1766–1769.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] In particular, Lagrange gave a proof that the Brouncker–Wallis algorithm always terminates.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Let $h_{i}/k_{i}$ denote the unique sequence of convergents of the regular continued fraction for ${\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Then the pair of positive integers $(x_{1},y_{1})$ solving Pell's equation and minimizing *x* satisfies *x*1 = *hi* and *y*1 = *ki* for some *i*.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] This pair is called the *fundamental solution*.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The sequence of integers $[a_{0};a_{1},a_{2},\ldots ]$ in the regular continued fraction of ${\sqrt {n}}$ is always eventually periodic.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Moreover, the tuple $(a_{1},a_{2},\ldots ,a_{r-1})$ is palindromic, the same left-to-right or right-to-left.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The computation time for finding the fundamental solution using the continued fraction method, with the aid of the Schönhage–Strassen algorithm for fast integer multiplication, is within a logarithmic factor of the solution size, the number of digits in the pair $(x_{1},y_{1})$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] However, this is not a polynomial-time algorithm because the number of digits in the solution may be as large as ${\sqrt {n}}$ , far larger than a polynomial in the number of digits in the input value *n*.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Once the fundamental solution is found, all remaining solutions may be calculated algebraically from $x_{k}+y_{k}{\sqrt {n}}=(x_{1}+y_{1}{\sqrt {n}})^{k},$ expanding the right side, equating coefficients of ${\sqrt {n}}$ on both sides, and equating the other terms on both sides.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] For instance, Archimedes' cattle problem is equivalent to the Pell equation $x^{2}-410\,286\,423\,278\,424\ y^{2}=1$ , the fundamental solution of which has 206545 digits if written out explicitly.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Methods related to the quadratic sieve approach for integer factorization may be used to collect relations between prime numbers in the number field generated by ${\sqrt {n}}$ and to combine these relations to find a product representation of this type.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The resulting algorithm for solving Pell's equation is more efficient than the continued fraction method, though it still takes more than polynomial time.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Under the assumption of the generalized Riemann hypothesis, it can be shown to take time $\exp O\left({\sqrt {\log N\cdot \log \log N}}\right),$ where *N* = log *n* is the input size, similarly to the quadratic sieve.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Hallgren showed that a quantum computer can find a product representation, as described above, for the solution to Pell's equation in polynomial time.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Hallgren's algorithm, which can be interpreted as an algorithm for finding the group of units of a real quadratic number field, was extended to more general fields by Schmidt and Völlmer.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Since the period has length 4 , which is an even number, the convergent producing the fundamental solution is obtained by truncating the continued fraction right before the end of the first occurrence of the period: $[2;\ 1,1,1]={\frac {8}{3}}$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] For this the fundamental solution is obtained by truncating the continued fraction right before the second occurrence of the period $[3;\ 1,1,1,1,6,1,1,1,1]={\frac {649}{180}}$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The smallest solution can be very large.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The following is a list of the fundamental solution to $x^{2}-ny^{2}=1$ with *n* ≤ 128.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] When *n* is an integer square, there is no solution except for the trivial solution (1, 0).
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The values of *x* are sequence A002350 and those of *y* are sequence A002349 in OEIS.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Pell's equation has connections to several other important subjects in mathematics.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Pell's equation is closely related to the theory of algebraic numbers, as the formula $x^{2}-ny^{2}=(x+y{\sqrt {n}})(x-y{\sqrt {n}})$ is the norm for the ring $\mathbb {Z} [{\sqrt {n}}]$ and for the closely related quadratic field $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {n}})$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Thus, a pair of integers $(x,y)$ solves Pell's equation if and only if $x+y{\sqrt {n}}$ is a unit with norm 1 in $\mathbb {Z} [{\sqrt {n}}]$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Dirichlet's unit theorem, that all units of $\mathbb {Z} [{\sqrt {n}}]$ can be expressed as powers of a single fundamental unit (and multiplication by a sign), is an algebraic restatement of the fact that all solutions to the Pell's equation can be generated from the fundamental solution.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The fundamental unit can in general be found by solving a Pell-like equation but it does not always correspond directly to the fundamental solution of Pell's equation itself, because the fundamental unit may have norm −1 rather than 1 and its coefficients may be half integers rather than integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The relationship to the continued fractions implies that the solutions to Pell's equation form a semigroup subset of the modular group.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Thus, for example, if *p* and *q* satisfy Pell's equation, then ${\begin{pmatrix}p&q\\nq&p\end{pmatrix}}$ is a matrix of unit determinant.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Products of such matrices take exactly the same form, and thus all such products yield solutions to Pell's equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Størmer's theorem applies Pell equations to find pairs of consecutive smooth numbers, positive integers whose prime factors are all smaller than a given value.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] As part of this theory, Størmer also investigated divisibility relations among solutions to Pell's equation; in particular, he showed that each solution other than the fundamental solution has a prime factor that does not divide *n*.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The negative Pell's equation is given by $x^{2}-ny^{2}=-1$ and has also been extensively studied.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] It can be solved by the same method of continued fractions and has solutions if and only if the period of the continued fraction has odd length.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] A necessary (but not sufficient) condition for solvability is that *n* is not divisible by 4 or by a prime of form 4*k* + 3.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The proportion of square-free *n* divisible by *k* primes of the form 4*m* + 1 for which the negative Pell's equation is solvable is at least *α*.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] As stated above, if the negative Pell's equation is solvable, a solution can be found using the method of continued fractions as in the positive Pell's equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The recursion relation works slightly differently however.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The equation $\textstyle u^{2}-nv^{2}=1$ is the corresponding **Pell's resolvent**.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] A recursive algorithm was given by Lagrange in 1768 for solving the equation, reducing the problem to the case $|N|<{\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Such solutions can be derived using the continued-fractions method as outlined above.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] There exists a finite set of solutions to $\textstyle x^{2}-ny^{2}=N$ such that every solution is a Pell multiple of a solution from that set.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] If *x* and *y* are positive integer solutions to the Pell's equation with $|N|<{\sqrt {n}}$ , then $x/y$ is a convergent to the continued fraction of ${\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] Solutions to the generalized Pell's equation are used for solving certain Diophantine equations and units of certain rings, and they arise in the study of SIC-POVMs in quantum information theory.
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] The equation $x^{2}-ny^{2}=4$ is similar to the resolvent $\textstyle x^{2}-ny^{2}=1$ in that if a minimal solution to $\textstyle x^{2}-ny^{2}=4$ can be found, then all solutions of the equation can be generated in a similar manner to the case $N=1$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/pell-s-equation] For certain n , solutions to $\textstyle x^{2}-ny^{2}=1$ can be generated from those with $\textstyle x^{2}-ny^{2}=4$ , in that if $n\equiv 5{\pmod {8}},$ then every third solution to $\textstyle x^{2}-ny^{2}=4$ has $x,y$ even, generating a solution to $\textstyle x^{2}-ny^{2}=1$ .
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] A **Pythagorean triple** consists of three positive integers a, b, and c, such that *a*2 + *b*2 = *c*2.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Such a triple is commonly written (*a*, *b*, *c*), a well-known example is (3, 4, 5).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] If (*a*, *b*, *c*) is a Pythagorean triple, then so is (*ka*, *kb*, *kc*) for any positive integer k.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] A triangle whose side lengths are a Pythagorean triple is a right triangle and called a **Pythagorean triangle**.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] A **primitive Pythagorean triple** is one in which a, b and c are coprime (that is, they have no common divisor larger than 1).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] For example, (3, 4, 5) is a primitive Pythagorean triple whereas (6, 8, 10) is not.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Every Pythagorean triple can be scaled to a unique primitive Pythagorean triple by dividing (*a*, *b*, *c*) by their greatest common divisor.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Conversely, every Pythagorean triple can be obtained by multiplying the elements of a primitive Pythagorean triple by a positive integer (the same for the three elements).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The name is derived from the Pythagorean theorem, stating that every right triangle has side lengths satisfying the formula $a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}$ ; thus, Pythagorean triples describe the three integer side lengths of a right triangle.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] However, right triangles with non-integer sides do not form Pythagorean triples.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] For instance, the triangle with sides $a=b=1$ and $c={\sqrt {2}}$ is a right triangle, but $(1,1,{\sqrt {2}})$ is not a Pythagorean triple because the square root of 2 is not an integer.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Moreover, 1 and ${\sqrt {2}}$ do not have an integer common multiple because ${\sqrt {2}}$ is irrational.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Pythagorean triples have been known since ancient times.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The oldest known record comes from Plimpton 322, a Babylonian clay tablet from about 1800 BC, written in a sexagesimal number system.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] When searching for integer solutions, the equation *a*2 + *b*2 = *c*2 is a Diophantine equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Thus Pythagorean triples are among the oldest known solutions of a nonlinear Diophantine equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Other small Pythagorean triples such as (6, 8, 10) are not listed because they are not primitive; for instance (6, 8, 10) is a multiple of (3, 4, 5).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Each of these points (with their multiples) forms a radiating line in the scatter plot to the right.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The triple generated by Euclid's formula is primitive if and only if m and n are coprime and exactly one of them is even.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] When both m and n are odd, then a, b, and c will be even, and the triple will not be primitive; however, dividing a, b, and c by 2 will yield a primitive triple when m and n are coprime.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Every primitive triple arises (after the exchange of a and b, if a is even) from a unique pair of coprime numbers m, n, one of which is even.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] It follows that there are infinitely many primitive Pythagorean triples.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] This relationship of a, b and c to m and n from Euclid's formula is referenced throughout the rest of this article.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Despite generating all primitive triples, Euclid's formula does not produce all triples—for example, (9, 12, 15) cannot be generated using integer m and n.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] where m, n, and k are positive integers with *m* > *n*, and with m and n coprime and not both odd.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] That these formulas generate Pythagorean triples can be verified by expanding *a*2 + *b*2 using elementary algebra and verifying that the result equals *c*2.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Since every Pythagorean triple can be divided through by some integer k to obtain a primitive triple, every triple can be generated uniquely by using the formula with m and n to generate its primitive counterpart and then multiplying through by k as in the last equation.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Choosing m and n from certain integer sequences gives interesting results.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] For example, if m and n are consecutive Pell numbers, a and b will differ by 1.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Many formulas for generating triples with particular properties have been developed since the time of Euclid.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] A proof of the *necessity* that *a, b, c* be expressed by Euclid's formula for any primitive Pythagorean triple is as follows.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] All such primitive triples can be written as (*a*, *b*, *c*) where *a*2 + *b*2 = *c*2 and a, b, c are coprime.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Thus a, b, c are pairwise coprime (if a prime number divided two of them, it would be forced also to divide the third one).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] As a and b are coprime, at least one of them is odd.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] If we suppose that a is odd, then b is even and c is odd (if both a and b were odd, c would be even, and *c*2 would be a multiple of 4, while *a*2 + *b*2 would be congruent to 2 modulo 4, as an odd square is congruent to 1 modulo 4).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] As ${\tfrac {m}{n}}$ is fully reduced, m and n are coprime, and they cannot both be even.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] If they were both odd, the numerator of ${\tfrac {m^{2}-n^{2}}{2mn}}$ would be a multiple of 4 (because an odd square is congruent to 1 modulo 4), and the denominator 2*mn* would not be a multiple of 4.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Since 4 would be the minimum possible even factor in the numerator and 2 would be the maximum possible even factor in the denominator, this would imply a to be even despite defining it as odd.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Thus one of m and n is odd and the other is even, and the numerators of the two fractions with denominator 2*mn* are odd.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Thus these fractions are fully reduced (an odd prime dividing this denominator divides one of m and n but not the other; thus it does not divide *m*2 ± *n*2).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] One may thus equate numerators with numerators and denominators with denominators, giving Euclid's formula $a=m^{2}-n^{2},\ \,b=2mn,\ \,c=m^{2}+n^{2}$ with m and n coprime and of opposite parities.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] A longer but more commonplace proof is given in Maor (2007) and Sierpiński (2003).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Another proof is given in Diophantine equation § Example of Pythagorean triples, as an instance of a general method that applies to every homogeneous Diophantine equation of degree two.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Suppose the sides of a Pythagorean triangle have lengths *m*2 − *n*2, 2*mn*, and *m*2 + *n*2, and suppose the angle between the leg of length *m*2 − *n*2 and the hypotenuse of length *m*2 + *n*2 is denoted as β.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The following variant of Euclid's formula is sometimes more convenient, as being more symmetric in m and n (same parity condition on m and n).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] If m and n are two odd integers such that *m* > *n*, then $a=mn,\quad b={\frac {m^{2}-n^{2}}{2}},\quad c={\frac {m^{2}+n^{2}}{2}}$ are three integers that form a Pythagorean triple, which is primitive if and only if m and n are coprime.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Conversely, every primitive Pythagorean triple arises (after the exchange of a and b, if a is even) from a unique pair *m* > *n* > 0 of coprime odd integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] In the presentation above, it is said that all Pythagorean triples are uniquely obtained from Euclid's formula "after the exchange of *a* and *b*, if *a* is even".
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Euclid's formula and the variant above can be merged as follows to avoid this exchange, leading to the following result.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Every primitive Pythagorean triple can be uniquely written $a=2\varepsilon mn,\quad b=\varepsilon (m^{2}-n^{2}),\quad c=\varepsilon (m^{2}+n^{2}),$ where m and n are positive coprime integers, and $\varepsilon ={\frac {1}{2}}$ if m and n are both odd, and $\varepsilon =1$ otherwise.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Equivalently, $\varepsilon ={\frac {1}{2}}$ if a is odd, and $\varepsilon =1$ if a is even.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] can be understood in terms of the geometry of rational points on the unit circle (Trautman 1998).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] In fact, a point in the Cartesian plane with coordinates (*x*, *y*) belongs to the unit circle if *x*2 + *y*2 = 1.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] By multiplying both members by *c*2, one can see that the rational points on the circle are in one-to-one correspondence with the primitive Pythagorean triples.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Note that *t* = *y* / (1 + *x*) = *b* / (*c* + *a*) = *n* / *m* is also the tangent of half of the angle that is opposite the triangle side of length b.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] There is a correspondence between points on the unit circle with rational coordinates and primitive Pythagorean triples.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] At this point, Euclid's formulae can be derived either by methods of trigonometry or equivalently by using the stereographic projection.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] This establishes that each rational point of the x-axis goes over to a rational point of the unit circle.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The converse, that every rational point of the unit circle comes from such a point of the x-axis, follows by applying the inverse stereographic projection.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Suppose that *P*(*x*, *y*) is a point of the unit circle with x and y rational numbers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] In terms of algebraic geometry, the algebraic variety of rational points on the unit circle is birational to the affine line over the rational numbers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The unit circle is thus called a rational curve, and it is this fact which enables an explicit parameterization of the (rational number) points on it by means of rational functions.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] A 2D lattice is a regular array of isolated points where if any one point is chosen as the Cartesian origin (0, 0), then all the other points are at (*x*, *y*) where x and y range over all positive and negative integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Any Pythagorean triangle with triple (*a*, *b*, *c*) can be drawn within a 2D lattice with vertices at coordinates (0, 0), (*a*, 0) and (0, *b*).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The first occurrence of two primitive Pythagorean triples sharing the same area occurs with triangles with sides (20, 21, 29), (12, 35, 37) and common area 210 (sequence A093536 in the OEIS).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The first occurrence of two primitive Pythagorean triples sharing the same interior lattice count occurs with (18108, 252685, 253333), (28077, 162964, 165365) and interior lattice count 2287674594 (sequence A225760 in the OEIS).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] As yet, no set of three primitive Pythagorean triples have been found sharing the same interior lattice count.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] By Euclid's formula all primitive Pythagorean triples can be generated from integers m and n with $m>n>0$ , $m+n$ odd and $\gcd(m,n)=1.$ Hence there is a 1 to 1 mapping of rationals (in lowest terms) to primitive Pythagorean triples where ${\tfrac {n}{m}}$ is in the interval $(0,1)$ and $m+n$ odd.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] In order to enumerate primitive Pythagorean triples the rational can be expressed as an ordered pair $(n,m)$ and mapped to an integer using a pairing function such as Cantor's pairing function.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] An example can be seen at (sequence A277557 in the OEIS).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Pythagorean triples can likewise be encoded into a square matrix of the form $X={\begin{bmatrix}c+b&a\\a&c-b\end{bmatrix}}.$ A matrix of this form is symmetric.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Furthermore, the determinant of X is $\det X=c^{2}-a^{2}-b^{2}\,$ which is zero precisely when (*a*,*b*,*c*) is a Pythagorean triple.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] If X corresponds to a Pythagorean triple, then as a matrix it must have rank 1.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] holds, where the T denotes the matrix transpose.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Since ξ and -ξ produce the same Pythagorean triple, the vector ξ can be considered a spinor (for the Lorentz group SO(1, 2)).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] In abstract terms, the Euclid formula means that each primitive Pythagorean triple can be written as the outer product with itself of a spinor with integer entries, as in (**1**).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] with determinant equal to one: *αδ* − *βγ* = 1.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] This set forms a group, since the inverse of a matrix in Γ is again in Γ, as is the product of two matrices in Γ.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The modular group acts on the collection of all integer spinors.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Furthermore, the group is transitive on the collection of integer spinors with relatively prime entries.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] where u and v are selected (by the Euclidean algorithm) so that *mu* + *nv* = 1.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] By acting on the spinor ξ in (**1**), the action of Γ goes over to an action on Pythagorean triples, provided one allows for triples with possibly negative components.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] gives rise to an action on the matrix X in (**1**).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] This does not give a well-defined action on primitive triples, since it may take a primitive triple to an imprimitive one.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] It is convenient at this point (per Trautman 1998) to call a triple (*a*,*b*,*c*) **standard** if *c* > 0 and either (*a*,*b*,*c*) are relatively prime or (*a*/2,*b*/2,*c*/2) are relatively prime with *a*/2 odd.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] If the spinor [*m* *n*]T has relatively prime entries, then the associated triple (*a*,*b*,*c*) determined by (**1**) is a standard triple.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] It follows that the action of the modular group is transitive on the set of standard triples.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Alternatively, restrict attention to those values of m and n for which m is odd and n is even.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] where SL(2,**Z**2) is the special linear group over the finite field **Z**2 of integers modulo 2.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Then Γ(2) is the group of unimodular transformations which preserve the parity of each entry.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Thus if the first entry of ξ is odd and the second entry is even, then the same is true of *A*ξ for all *A* ∈ Γ(2).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] In fact, under the action (**2**), the group Γ(2) acts transitively on the collection of primitive Pythagorean triples (Alperin 2005).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The group Γ(2) is the free group whose generators are the matrices $U={\begin{bmatrix}1&2\\0&1\end{bmatrix}},\qquad L={\begin{bmatrix}1&0\\2&1\end{bmatrix}}.$ Consequently, every primitive Pythagorean triple can be obtained in a unique way as a product of copies of the matrices U and L.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] In other words, every primitive triple will be a "parent" to three additional primitive triples.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The linear transformations T1, T2, and T3 have a geometric interpretation in the language of quadratic forms.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] They are closely related to (but are not equal to) reflections generating the orthogonal group of *x*2 + *y*2 − *z*2 over the integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Alternatively, Euclid's formulae can be analyzed and proved using the Gaussian integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Gaussian integers are complex numbers of the form *α* = *u* + *vi*, where u and v are ordinary integers and i is the square root of negative one.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The units of Gaussian integers are ±1 and ±i.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The ordinary integers are called the rational integers and denoted as '**Z**'.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The Gaussian integers are denoted as **Z**[*i*].
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] A primitive Pythagorean triple is one in which a and b are coprime, i.e., they share no prime factors in the integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] For such a triple, either a or b is even, and the other is odd; from this, it follows that c is also odd.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The two factors *z* := *a* + *bi* and *z** := *a* − *bi* of a primitive Pythagorean triple each equal the square of a Gaussian integer.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] This can be proved using the property that every Gaussian integer can be factored uniquely into Gaussian primes up to units.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] (This unique factorization follows from the fact that, roughly speaking, a version of the Euclidean algorithm can be defined on them.) The proof has three steps.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] First, if a and b share no prime factors in the integers, then they also share no prime factors in the Gaussian integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] (Assume *a* = *gu* and *b* = *gv* with Gaussian integers g, u and v and g not a unit.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Then u and v lie on the same line through the origin.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] All Gaussian integers on such a line are integer multiples of some Gaussian integer h.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] But then the integer *gh* ≠ ±1 divides both a and b.) Second, it follows that z and *z** likewise share no prime factors in the Gaussian integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] For if they did, then their common divisor δ would also divide *z* + *z** = 2*a* and *z* − *z** = 2*ib*.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Since a and b are coprime, that implies that δ divides 2 = (1 + i)(1 − i) = i(1 − i)2.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] From the formula *c*2 = *zz**, that in turn would imply that c is even, contrary to the hypothesis of a primitive Pythagorean triple.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Third, since *c*2 is a square, every Gaussian prime in its factorization is doubled, i.e., appears an even number of times.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Since z and *z** share no prime factors, this doubling is also true for them.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] For any primitive Pythagorean triple, there must be integers m and n such that these two equations are satisfied.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Hence, every Pythagorean triple can be generated from some choice of these integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] If we consider the square of a Gaussian integer we get the following direct interpretation of Euclid's formula as representing the perfect square of a Gaussian integer.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Using the facts that the Gaussian integers are a Euclidean domain and that for a Gaussian integer p $|p|^{2}$ is always a square it is possible to show that a Pythagorean triple corresponds to the square of a prime Gaussian integer if the hypotenuse is prime.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] If the Gaussian integer is not prime then it is the product of two Gaussian integers p and q with $|p|^{2}$ and $|q|^{2}$ integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Since magnitudes multiply in the Gaussian integers, the product must be $|p||q|$ , which when squared to find a Pythagorean triple must be composite.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] There are a number of results on the distribution of Pythagorean triples.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] In the scatter plot, a number of obvious patterns are already apparent.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Whenever the legs (*a*,*b*) of a primitive triple appear in the plot, all integer multiples of (*a*,*b*) must also appear in the plot, and this property produces the appearance of lines radiating from the origin in the diagram.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Within the scatter, there are sets of parabolic patterns with a high density of points and all their foci at the origin, opening up in all four directions.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Different parabolas intersect at the axes and appear to reflect off the axis with an incidence angle of 45 degrees, with a third parabola entering in a perpendicular fashion.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Within this quadrant, each arc centered on the origin shows that section of the parabola that lies between its tip and its intersection with its semi-latus rectum.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] These patterns can be explained as follows.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] If a is varied for a given n (i.e. on a given parabola), integer values of b occur relatively frequently if n is a square or a small multiple of a square.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] If several such values happen to lie close together, the corresponding parabolas approximately coincide, and the triples cluster in a narrow parabolic strip.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The angular properties described above follow immediately from the functional form of the parabolas.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The parabolas are reflected at the a-axis at *a* = 2*n*, and the derivative of b with respect to a at this point is –1; hence the incidence angle is 45°.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Since the clusters, like all triples, are repeated at integer multiples, the value 2*n* also corresponds to a cluster.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The corresponding parabola intersects the b-axis at right angles at *b* = 2*n*, and hence its reflection upon interchange of a and b intersects the a-axis at right angles at *a* = 2*n*, precisely where the parabola for n is reflected at the a-axis.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Albert Fässler and others provide insights into the significance of these parabolas in the context of conformal mappings.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The case *n* = 1 of the more general construction of Pythagorean triples has been known for a long time.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] It can be shown that all Pythagorean triples can be obtained, with appropriate rescaling, from the basic Platonic sequence (a, (*a*2 − 1)/2 and (*a*2 + 1)/2) by allowing a to take non-integer rational values.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] If a is replaced with the fraction *m*/*n* in the sequence, the result is equal to the 'standard' triple generator (2*mn*, *m*2 − *n*2,*m*2 + *n*2) after rescaling.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] It follows that every triple has a corresponding rational a value which can be used to generate a similar triangle (one with the same three angles and with sides in the same proportions as the original).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The Platonic sequence itself can be derived by following the steps for 'splitting the square' described in Diophantus II.VIII.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The arithmetic progressions of three squares are in one-to-one correspondence with Pythgorean triples.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] As these transformations are inverse to each other, they define the announced one-to-one correspondence.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] This one-to-one correspondence implies that almost all properties of arithmetic progressions of squares are easily deduced from a corresponding property of Pythagorean triples.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] In particular, Euclid's formula implies that all arithmetic progressions of three squares can be obtained as $(m^{2}-n^{2}-2mn)^{2},\quad (m^{2}+m^{2})^{2},\quad (m^{2}-n^{2}+2mn)^{2},$ where ⁠ m ⁠ and ⁠ n ⁠ are two arbitrary positive integers of different parities.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Also, the difference $z^{2}-y^{2}=y^{2}-x^{2}$ between two consecutive squares in an arithmetic progression of squares is always a multiple of 24.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] This results from the divisibility relations given in § General properties, since this difference is ⁠ $2ab$ ⁠, where ⁠ a ⁠ and ⁠ b ⁠ are the first elements of the associated Euclidean triple.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] There is an infinite number of solutions to this equation as solving for the variables involves an elliptic curve.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] and was first solved by Euler as $a,b,c,d=133,59,158,134.$ Since he showed this is a rational point in an elliptic curve, then there is an infinite number of solutions.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] In fact, he also found a 7th degree polynomial parameterization.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] with small solutions as $a,b,c,d=3,5,8,14$ and can be solved as binary quadratic forms.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] No Pythagorean triples are isosceles, because the ratio of the hypotenuse to either other side is √2, but √2 cannot be expressed as the ratio of 2 integers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] This sequence of primitive Pythagorean triples forms the central stem (trunk) of the rooted ternary tree of primitive Pythagorean triples.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] where integer $m>0$ is the generating parameter.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] It shows that all odd numbers (greater than 1) appear in this type of almost-isosceles primitive Pythagorean triple.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] This sequence of primitive Pythagorean triples forms the right hand side outer stem of the rooted ternary tree of primitive Pythagorean triples.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] Another property of this type of almost-isosceles primitive Pythagorean triple is that the sides are related such that $a^{b}+b^{a}=Kc$ for some integer K .
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p01] The middle side of each of these triangles is the sum of the three sides of the preceding triangle.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] There are several ways to generalize the concept of Pythagorean triples.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] The Pythagorean n-tuple can be made primitive by dividing out by the largest common divisor of its values.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] Furthermore, any primitive Pythagorean n-tuple *a*2 1 + ... + *a*2 *n* = *c*2 can be found by this approach.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] Use (*m*1, ..., *m**n*) = (*c* + *a*1, *a*2, ..., *a**n*) to get a Pythagorean n-tuple by the above formula and divide out by the largest common integer divisor, which is 2*m*1 = 2(*c* + *a*1).
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] and *v* ≥ 5 is any integer not divisible by 2 or 3.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] a fact which is connected to the Leech lattice.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] A generalization of the concept of Pythagorean triples is the search for triples of positive integers a, b, and c, such that *a**n* + *b**n* = *c**n*, for some n strictly greater than 2.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] Pierre de Fermat in 1637 claimed that no such triple exists, a claim that came to be known as Fermat's Last Theorem because it took longer than any other conjecture by Fermat to be proved or disproved.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] The first proof was given by Andrew Wiles in 1994.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] Another generalization is searching for sequences of *n* + 1 positive integers for which the nth power of the last is the sum of the nth powers of the previous terms.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] For the *n* = 3 case, in which $x^{3}+y^{3}+z^{3}=w^{3},$ called the Fermat cubic, a general formula exists giving all solutions.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] A slightly different generalization allows the sum of (*k* + 1) nth powers to equal the sum of (*n* − *k*) nth powers.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] There can also exist *n* − 1 positive integers whose nth powers sum to an nth power (though, by Fermat's Last Theorem, not for *n* = 3); these are counterexamples to Euler's sum of powers conjecture.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] A **Heronian triangle** is commonly defined as one with integer sides whose area is also an integer.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] The lengths of the sides of such a triangle form a **Heronian triple** (*a, b, c*) for *a* ≤ *b* ≤ *c*.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] Every Pythagorean triple is a Heronian triple, because at least one of the legs a, b must be even in a Pythagorean triple, so the area *ab*/2 is an integer.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] Not every Heronian triple is a Pythagorean triple, however, as the example (4, 13, 15) with area 24 shows.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] If (*a*, *b*, *c*) is a Heronian triple, so is (*ka*, *kb*, *kc*) where k is any positive integer; its area will be the integer that is *k*2 times the integer area of the (*a*, *b*, *c*) triangle.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] The Heronian triple (*a*, *b*, *c*) is **primitive** provided *a*, *b*, *c* are setwise coprime.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] be a nonzero perfect square divisible by 16.
[src:diophantine-equations/pythagorean-triple-p02] Primitive Pythagorean triples have been used in cryptography as random sequences and for the generation of keys.
